6 July 2020

INTRODUCTION¶

Forecasting the sales quantity of a product for an online retail is a challenging task. Forecasting heavily relies on the historical data and your modeling skills. In this project, forecasting methods are developed to predict the next day’s sales quantity of 8 products sold in Trendyol. The products are La Roche Posay Facial Cleanser, Sleepy Wet Towel, Xiaomi Bluetooth Headphone, Fakir Sweeper, Trendyolmilla Tight Trousers, Oral-B Re-chargeable Toothbrush, Trendyolmilla Bikini Top and Koton Coat.

This project is organized as live competition in which daily submissions are made by groups via application programming interface (API). The aim of this project is to make students develop a forecasting product. Developed product can be used in various business areas, such as setting up appropriate inventory or service levels. Accurate forecasts help businesses in reducing waste and understanding the uncertainty and its risk implications. The provided data covers daily sales of eight products of Trendyol and includes product, price, sold count, visit count, favored count, basket count, category sold, category brand sold, category visits and trendyol visits. Since the day of the week, special events and other can be important for forecasting, we used a dataset called “Calender Data”. Calender data includes the data related to that data; for example month info, quarter info, day of the week info, weekday / weekend / business day info, holiday and ramadan info etc. Moreover, we included Google trends data in order to make a comparison between the site visits of Hepsiburada and Trendyol.

After merging these three datasets, merged data is divided into groups in a way that there are different dataframes for each product. Every dataframes are plotted and their behavior is observed. In preprocesing part, average sold count of each product is checked. If the average sold count is more than 5 products per day, the days with 0 sold count are deleted. Because, for these products the data is missing. However, for Trendyolmilla Bikini Top and Koton Coat, average sold count is less than 5 and 0 sold count days might be real data, so they are kept. Then, the days with -1 values are deleted and if the -1 values are making more than 50% of the whole data on that column, whole column is deleted. Because missing data may lead to inconsistencies. If the days with -1 values are making less than 50% of the whole data on that column, the column is kept and missing values are filled with linear interpolation. At the end of preprocessing, missing days are filled with forward fill. In the “Feature Engineering” part, linear regression is made and two models are created for each product. Trim model includes only the significant features with p<0.1. Full model includes all the features in the dataframe. Then these two models are compared. If trim regression model (model with all features have p-value less than 0.10) have a better AIC, nonsignificant values are deleted. If ful model gives a better AIC value, then all features are kept. With the decided models, the data is visualized.

After manipulating the data, literature review is made and several models are used to forecast product sales. In this project Sarima, Sarimax, Naive Forecasts, Arima, Error Prediction with Arima, ETS and Error Prediction with ETS are used which will be explained in detail in Approach part.

Between these models, the one with the best cross validation score is selected and submitted. Each group’s performance is measured by “Weighted Mean Absolute Percentage Error” (WMAPE) of their prediction. The lower the WMAPE score the better the prediction.

RELATED LITERATURE¶

Broadly speaking, in Time Series Modeling and Forecasting article by Adhikari and Agrawal [1], they have presented a state-of-the-art of some popular time series forecasting models such as ARIMA models for linear time series forecasting with their salient features. This article has been seen that, the proper selection of the model orders (in case of ARIMA), the number of inputs, hidden and output neurons and the constant hyper-parameters is extremely crucial for successful forecasting. Moreover, the one important function, AIC, is discussed which are frequently used for ARIMA model selection. For selecting the number of constant hyper-parameters (different p, d and q parameters used in our term project), cross validation should be carried out. Furthermore, a few important performance measures for evaluating the accuracy of forecasting models are considered in this article. To be able to obtain a reasonable knowledge about the overall forecasting error, more than one measure should be used in practice. Because of this reason, using different data sets, and different performance measures for models is an important satisfactory way.

On the other hand, in some cases, significant deviation can be seen among the original observations and the forecasted values. In such cases, a suitable data preprocessing, other than those used in the work may improve the forecast performances.

APPROACH¶

The data for each product is split into train and test set. To find the best predictive model, 6 different modelling approaches are used. Among these alternatives the model with the smallest MAPE score in the test set is used to make the daily predictions.

ARIMA¶

The first model tried is an ARIMA model. Regressors are not used in this model. To find the best seasonal parameter (m), different m values up to 13 are examined in a for loop. In the for loop, auto arima function is used in the test set. By doing this, the best ARIMA model is found for this specific seasonality case. Auto arima gives the model with the smallest AIC for the specific m value. After the model find the best models for each m value, these models are compared to each other. Model with the smallest AIC value is selected. Then the selected model is used to make forecasts. To be able to compare different models, MAPE score is calculated using the test set. The advantage of the model is being fast. However, the model’s prediction power is not high since explanatory regressors are not used.

ARIMAX¶

This model tries to forecast sales using time series data and additional regressors. To understand the regressors affecting the sales, linear regression is applied. The significant parameters are used as regressors in ARIMAX model. Seasonality is neglected in this model because the regressors such as day of month, weekday are used to determine the seasonality effect. The for loop used in the previous model to find the best m value is not used in this model.

ARIMAX using Cross Validation¶

The third model is an ARIMA model. In this ARIMA model, model parameters p,d,q are found with cross validation in train set. Different p,d,q values are tried to find the best model:

• p=”0”,”1”,”2”,”3”

• d=”0”,”1”

• q=”0”,”1”,”2”,”3”

The 32 different alternatives are compared using the train data. Using cross validation, the best model is selected as the one with having the lowest MAPE score. After selecting the best model among 32 alternatives, MAPE score for the test data is calculated to compare with the other models.

Regression + Residual Modelling with ARIMA using Cross Validation¶

Since the regression is used previously to find the significant features, it can be used to predict the sales demand. However, its residuals should be normally distributed. Moreover, since its residuals are also a time series data, it can be modeled with ARIMA or SARIMA model. Then, the prediction from regression and the prediction from time series residuals modelling are added to predict the corresponding sales demand. By doing that, 3 different trend alternative, “c”, “t” and “ct” are added to the grid search, and therefore parameter space consists of 96 different alternatives. They are evaluated in the train set with the cross-validation perspective and the best possible model is evaluated in the test set. Later, the MAPE score of this approach is recorded to compare with the other models.

ETS models using Cross Validation¶

Since ETS (error,trend,seasonality) models can also be used with univariate time series data,the sales demand is modeled without the regressors. Different t,s,p values are tried to find the best model:

• t = ['add', 'mul']

• s = ['add', 'mul']

• p = [2,3,4,7,12]

where t,s and p correspond to trend component, seasonality component and the seasonality period respectively.

Cross validation is used to find the best model among the alternatives and MAPE score of the best model is recorded.

Residual modelling with ETS approach using Cross Validation¶

Since ETS models require univariate time series data, it performs poorly compared to the other approaches. Therefore, residuals from regression model are used also as a univariate time series data and it is modeled with different t,s,p alternatives. The best model is found using cross validation in the train data and it is used to predict the residuals. These predictions are combined with the regression predictios to achieve the demand sales prediction for the test set. Then the MAPE score in the test set is recorded.

RESULTS¶

In this part of the report, submissions that are made during the project will be given. As described in the previous section, we have six different forecasting models for making predictions. After we constructed those models, we performed several analysis on test data. Initially, we made predictions for those six models and calculated MAPE values for different models. Then, the best model giving the least MAPE value is selected for submission for each day.

CONCLUSION¶

Forecasting is to estimate the value of an unknown parameter using the known parameters for a future state. It is necessary to carry out an effective sales forecasting to achieve powerful order planning for e-commerce companies. In this respect, sales forecasting plays a key role in the success of business enterprises. In this study, the e-commerce sales time series of many products from Trendyol Company in Turkey as empirical analysis data set merging with calendar dataset and google trend dataset and forecast the time series of daily sales by using Sarima, Sarimax, Arimax with Cross Validation, Error Prediction with Arimax using cross validation, ETS and Error Prediction with ETS model are worked.

For data preprocessing, sold_count mean of each product are calculated and if sold_count mean is greater than 5, then missing values are not considering otherwise they are taken. Some other preprocessing steps are as follow:

• High missing rate columns are dropped. (If missing_rate > 50%)

• Missing dates are added to the dataset.

• Low missing rate columns are filled by using linear interpolation.

For time series modeling, WMAPE values, which are the performance criterion of all methods, are calculated. When we compare the WMAPE for each model, it can be understood that using there is no best model to give best forecast prediction for all products but for every single product, one time series model is selected to make best prediction of sales quantity.

For future works, cross relations between products can be considering. This could lead to clusters of products that behave coherently. The idea comes from that, some products are complementary to another ones, so considering cross relation between sales relation of products may increase accuracy of our time series sales quantity forecast results. The principle of this study can be used in the real application of e-commerce companies to predict the sales of various forms of products. Depending on the sales frequency of different types of products, different forecasting models can be selected to use this more effective to predict sales in a future period. Therefore, according to this precise forecast, the enterprise's inventory strategy and logistics strategy can be more rationally formulated so that the entire supply chain can operate more smoothly.

Reference¶

Adhikari, Ratnadip & Agrawal, R.. (2013). An Introductory Study on Time series Modeling and Forecasting. 10.13140/2.1.2771.8084.

FEATURE ENGINEERING¶

Select the significant features by looking at its p-value in the regression

If trim regression model( model with all features have p-value less than 0.10) have a better AIC, remove other columns

Else use all features because its model (full_model) gives the better AIC

In [220]:
#prod_1=prod_1.loc[:,(np.abs(prod_1.corr()["sold_count"]).values)>0.10]
reg_models=[]
train_dfs=[]
test_dfs=[]
for i in range(len(processed_df_train_list)):
    print((product_list[i]))
    prod_1_X=processed_df_train_list[i].drop("sold_count",1)
    prod_1_y=(processed_df_train_list[i].sold_count)
    #prod_1_X=sm.add_constant(prod_1_X)
    
        
    reg_obj=sm.OLS(prod_1_y,prod_1_X).fit()
    
    prod_1_X_trimmed=prod_1_X.iloc[:,(reg_obj.pvalues<0.10).values]
    reg_obj_final=sm.OLS(prod_1_y,prod_1_X_trimmed).fit()
    

    test_dfs.append(prod_1_y)
    print("R2 values for normal and trim models are:",reg_obj.rsquared_adj,reg_obj_final.rsquared_adj)
    print("AIC values for normal and trim models are:",reg_obj.aic,reg_obj_final.aic)
    if(reg_obj_final.aic<reg_obj.aic):
        my_reg=reg_obj_final
        my_df=prod_1_X_trimmed
        reg_models.append(my_reg)
        train_dfs.append(my_df)
        
    else:
        my_reg=reg_obj
        my_df=prod_1_X
        reg_models.append(my_reg)
        train_dfs.append(my_df)

Autocorrelation and Partial Autocorrelation</a>¶

  • Autocorrelation - The autocorrelation function (ACF) measures how a series is correlated with itself at different lags.
  • Partial Autocorrelation - The partial autocorrelation function can be interpreted as a regression of the series against its past lags. The terms can be interpreted the same way as a standard linear regression, that is the contribution of a change in that particular lag while holding others constant.

def sarima_configs(index=None):
    models = list()
    # define config lists
    p_params = [0,1,2,3]
    d_params = [0, 1]
    q_params = [0,1,2,3]
    t_params = ['c','t','ct']
   
    # create config instances
    if index=="sarimax":
        print("for sarimax")
        for p in p_params:
            for d in d_params:
                for q in q_params:
                    cfg = (p,d,q)
                    models.append(cfg)
    else:
        for p in p_params:
            for d in d_params:
                for q in q_params:
                    for t in t_params:

                        cfg = [(p,d,q), t]
                        models.append(cfg)
    return models

def sarima_forecast(data,config,exog=None):
    
    try:
        order, trend = config
        print(config)
        model = pm.ARIMA(order=order,trend=trend, enforce_stationarity=False, enforce_invertibility=False,suppress_warnings=True)
    except:
        order = config
        print(config)
        model = pm.ARIMA(order=order, enforce_stationarity=False, enforce_invertibility=False,suppress_warnings=True)

    cv = SlidingWindowForecastCV(window_size=int(len(data)*0.95),h=2) 
    
    if isinstance(exog,pd.DataFrame):
        model_cv_scores=pm.model_selection.cross_val_score(model, data, exog,scoring='smape', cv=cv)
    else:
        model_cv_scores=pm.model_selection.cross_val_score(model, data,scoring='smape', cv=cv)
    model_error=np.mean(model_cv_scores)
    
    return model_error,model

# create a set of exponential smoothing configs to try
def exp_smoothing_configs(seasonal=[None]):
    models = list()
    # define config lists
    t_params = ['add', 'mul']
   
    s_params = ['add', 'mul']
    p_params = [2,3,4,7,12]
    
   
    
    # create config instances
    for t in t_params:
        
        for s in s_params:
            for p in p_params:
                cfg = [t,s,p]
                models.append(cfg)
    return models

def exp_model(data,config):
    
    errors=[]
    cv = SlidingWindowForecastCV(window_size=int(len(data)*0.95),h=2)#change
    cv_generator = cv.split(data)
    error_total=0
    counter=0
    for train_index,test_index in (cv_generator):
        
        t,s,p = config
       
        try:
            model = ExponentialSmoothing(data[train_index], trend=t,seasonal=s,seasonal_periods=int(p),freq="D")
            model_fit=model.fit()
            #print("actual is:",data[test].values)
            pred=model_fit.forecast(2).values #change
            #print("pred is:",pred)

            error=np.abs((data[test_index].values-pred)/(data[test_index].values))
            #print("error is:",np.mean(error))
            error_total+=np.mean(error)
            counter+=1
            
        except:
            return None,10**6
   
    mape=error_total/counter
    
    return model,mape
